# sentence_id = 55
# document_id = 0086-034
# subdoc = 4.14
# prose_translation = Arising then at first from improvisations (both Tragedy and Comedy—the former from the leaders of the Dithyramb, the latter from the leaders of the phallic songs, which even now remain in use in many cities), Tragedy grew little by little as they developed as much of it as became apparent; and after undergoing many changes, Tragedy stopped when it achieved its own natural form.
# literal_translation = Having-become but therefore from beginning improvisational both itself and the comedy, and the-one indeed from the [ones] leading-off the dithyramb, the-other but from the the phallic-songs, which still even now in many of-the cities remains customary, according-to small [degree] was-increased [by those] leading-forward as-much-as became apparent of-it, and many changes having-changed the tragedy stopped, when it-had the of-itself nature.
