# sentence_id = 201
# translation_lang = en
# prose_translation = Since, then, the structure of the finest tragedy should be not simple but complex, and since it should represent fearsome and pitiable events (for this is the peculiar characteristic of this kind of representation), it is first of all clear that decent men should not be seen changing from good fortune to bad fortune (for this is not fearsome or pitiable, but morally repulsive), nor should villainous men be seen changing from misfortune to good fortune (for this is the most untragic of all).
# literal_translation = Since therefore it-is-necessary the structure of-the finest tragedy not simple but complex to-be, and this of-fearsome and of-pitiable to-be imitative (this for peculiar of-the such imitation is), first indeed [it is] clear that neither the decent men it-is-necessary changing to-appear from good-fortune into misfortune (not for fearsome nor pitiable this [is], but loathsome it-is) nor the villainous [men] from misfortune into good-fortune (most-untragic for this is of-all).
