# sentence_id = 457
# document_id = 0086-034
# subdoc = 23.1
# translation_lang = en
# prose_translation = As for narrative imitation in verse, it is clear that the plots should be dramatically constructed, just as in tragedies, and should center on a single action that is whole and complete—possessing a beginning, middle, and end—so that, like a single organic creature, it may produce its own proper pleasure. Furthermore, it should not resemble our usual histories, which necessarily provide an account not of a single action but of a single period of time, recording everything that happened during that period to one or more people, even though these events have only a chance relationship to one another.
# literal_translation = Concerning but the narrative and in meter imitative, that it is necessary the plots just as in the tragedies to construct dramatic, and about one action whole and complete, having beginning and middle and end, so that just as a living thing one whole it might make the proper pleasure, [it is] clear, and not like histories the usual to be, in which [is] necessity not of one action to make a declaration but of one time, as many things as in this happened about one or more, of which each as it chanced has toward each other.
